Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Meanwhile, halve and peel the @red onion{1}, then cut each half into 3 wedges. Trim the @carrot{2}, then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Cut into roughly 1cm wide, 5cm long batons.

Quarter and core the @apple{1}(quartered and cored) (no need to peel). Cut each quarter in half lengthways to make wedges.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams}(peeled if preferred) into 2cm chunks.

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil for the potatoes.

Meanwhile, pop the onion, carrot and apple into a large ovenproof #baking dish{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

Place the @British Cumberland sausages{8} on top of the veg, then roast on the middle shelf of your oven until the veg is tender and the sausages are cooked through, ~{30-35%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw sausages. They're cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, when the water is boiling, add the potatoes to the pan and cook until you can easily slip a knife through, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Pour the @water for the jus{200%milliliters} into another small saucepan. Bring to the boil on high heat.

Stir in the @red wine jus paste{22%grams}, then reduce the heat to medium-high. Allow the sauce to bubble and thicken, stirring regularly, ~{7-8%minutes}.

Once thickened, remove from the heat.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan, off the heat.

Add a knob of @butter{knob} and a splash of @?milk{splash} (if you have any) and mash until smooth using a #potato masher{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cover to keep warm.

Just before everything's ready, reheat the jus if needed.

Share the sausage, apple and root veg traybake out between your plates.

Serve the mash on the side and pour over the red wine jus to finish.

Enjoy!